<task>
Grade the diff against the spec on these axes:
- **Spec compliance** — does every Requirement in `.devlyn/criteria.generated.md` have code that satisfies it? Quote file:line.
- **Scope** — does the diff touch only `bin/cli.js` and `tests/cli.test.js` (the plan's authorized surface)? Any other file changed = HIGH finding `scope.out-of-scope-violation`.
- **Quality** — idiomatic patterns vs hand-rolled reinvention. `design.unidiomatic-pattern` MEDIUM if applicable.
- **Consistency** — style/naming/error-shape consistency with surrounding code (e.g. does the new `--format` parsing follow the same shape as the existing `--name` flag parsing in `parseNameFlag`?).

Clause-level check: the Requirements encode at least 3 distinct output-shape/exit-code clauses (bare version exit 0, `--format json` exit 0 with exact JSON body, unsupported `--format` value exit 1). Trace the code path for each. Also check: does ANY unsupported value (not just `yaml`) correctly hit the error path — e.g. `--format xml`, `--format` with no following value, `--format` value that happens to look like `json` but isn't (case sensitivity, e.g. `JSON`)? If the code only special-cases `yaml` rather than "anything not literally `json`", that is a spec violation — emit a HIGH finding.

Interaction check: verify the bare-`version` path never accidentally emits JSON-shaped output and the `--format json` path never emits the bare string — construct and run at least one command exercising each of the 4 verification commands from the generated criteria, plus one extra unsupported-value input not already covered by the existing tests (e.g. `--format xml` or `--format JSON` uppercase) to confirm the "any other unsupported value" clause truly generalizes rather than special-casing `yaml`. You may execute `node bin/cli.js version ...` commands read-only (they do not mutate any tracked file). Do not run anything that writes to the repo.

Coverage check: if you cannot exercise some axis, say so explicitly rather than assuming pass.

Anti-self-filter: report every finding you observe, including low-severity/low-confidence ones. Tag each with `confidence: high|medium|low`.
</task>

<output_contract>
